      <!-- Section 1: The AEO Definition -->
      <section id="definition" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>The AEO Definition</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Answer engine optimisation (AEO) is the practice of structuring website content so that answer engines can extract and surface it as a direct response to user queries, replacing or supplementing the traditional model of providing a ranked list of links for the user to investigate.</strong>
        </p>

        <p>
          The term entered digital marketing usage as Google introduced featured snippets — the first widely used answer engine format — and has since expanded to encompass optimisation for the full range of direct-answer interfaces: AI Overviews, People Also Ask boxes, voice assistant responses, and LLM-powered search platforms like Perplexity and Microsoft Copilot.
        </p>

        <p>
          The defining characteristic of AEO, as distinct from traditional search engine optimisation, is the shift in optimisation target. Traditional SEO targets a position in a ranked list. AEO targets selection as the answer — the content that is extracted, synthesised, or quoted directly to the user. This distinction has significant implications for content structure, schema implementation, and success measurement.
        </p>

        <p>
          AEO is classified as a subset of <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">generative engine optimisation (GEO)</a>, which is the broader discipline covering optimisation across all AI-driven search surfaces. For a detailed exploration of what AEO is and how it works, see the <a href="/what-is-aeo/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">What Is AEO guide</a>.
        </p>
