                <td class="px-5 py-3 align-top font-mono text-xs text-[var(--accent)]">—</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3 align-top">Machine-readable markup, typically in JSON-LD format using Schema.org vocabulary, that signals the type, purpose, and attributes of web content to search engines and AI systems. FAQPage, Article, HowTo, and Product schemas are the most relevant to AEO.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-[var(--line-soft)]">
                <td class="px-5 py-3 font-medium text-ink-100 align-top">Entity</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3 align-top font-mono text-xs text-[var(--accent)]">—</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3 align-top">A distinct, identifiable thing — organisation, person, place, product, or concept — that AI systems represent as a node in a knowledge graph. Strong entity authority means AI systems can reliably identify, classify, and cite your brand. Weak entity authority leads to omission or misrepresentation in generated answers.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-5 py-3 font-medium text-ink-100 align-top">Voice Search</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3 align-top font-mono text-xs text-[var(--accent)]">—</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3 align-top">Queries submitted via voice assistant (Siri, Alexa, Google Assistant) that receive a single spoken answer. The single-answer model makes AEO binary for voice queries: either your content is selected, or it is invisible. Voice search disproportionately targets featured snippet content and Knowledge Graph facts.</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
