      <!-- Section 3: AEO in Context -->
      <section id="aeo-in-context" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>AEO in Context: The Search Landscape Shift</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>AEO emerged as a discipline because search engines fundamentally changed their model — from curating lists of links to generating direct answers.</strong>
          Understanding the historical context clarifies why AEO requires different techniques from traditional SEO.
        </p>

        <p>
          Google's introduction of featured snippets in 2014 marked the first structural shift towards answer delivery. For the first time, a search engine was selecting specific content from specific pages and presenting it above the organic results, without requiring the user to click through. This created a new optimisation target: not rank position, but extraction eligibility.
        </p>

        <p>
          The introduction of voice search through Google Assistant, Alexa, and Siri intensified the shift. Voice interfaces deliver a single response and end the interaction. For voice-first queries — which tend to be more conversational and longer-tail than typed queries — the featured snippet model extends to a zero-choice environment: one answer, one source, binary visibility.
        </p>

        <p>
          The acceleration of large language model technology from 2022 onwards fundamentally changed the scale of the challenge. Platforms like ChatGPT, Perplexity, and Copilot process hundreds of millions of queries per month using generative models that synthesise answers from multiple sources. The selection criteria differ from featured snippets — these systems evaluate entity authority, content citability, and source credibility rather than simply extracting text passages. AEO, as a practice, has expanded to encompass these criteria alongside the original featured-snippet optimisation techniques.
        </p>

        <p>
          The result is a search landscape where a substantial portion of informational queries — particularly definitional, procedural, and comparison queries — are answered before the user ever reaches a traditional search results page. Brands without an AEO strategy are increasingly invisible at the top of the research funnel.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 4: Why Precise Definitions Matter -->
      <section id="why-definitions-matter" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Why Precise Definitions Matter in AEO</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Precise, consistent terminology is an operational requirement in AEO, not merely good practice — LLMs and structured data systems both rely on unambiguous language to classify and extract content correctly.</strong>
        </p>

        <p>
          When an AI system processes a page about "answer engine optimisation," it uses entity resolution to determine what concept the page discusses, how that concept relates to adjacent concepts (SEO, GEO, featured snippets), and whether the page is an authoritative source. Inconsistent terminology — alternating between "AEO," "answer engine optimisation," "voice search optimisation," and "featured snippet optimisation" without establishing the relationship between these terms — creates ambiguity that reduces the system's confidence in selecting the page as an answer source.
        </p>

        <p>
          For structured data, the same principle applies. FAQPage schema maps specific question strings to specific answer strings. If the question in the schema does not match the question a user is likely to ask, the schema provides no selection benefit. Writing schema questions in natural language that mirrors actual search queries — and keeping answers precise and self-contained — is an AEO-specific writing discipline.
        </p>

        <p>
          This is why this page exists alongside the broader <a href="/what-is-aeo/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">What Is AEO</a> and <a href="/answer-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">Answer Engine Optimisation</a> guides. A glossary-style definitional page provides clean, machine-extractable definitions that LLMs can quote verbatim when answering "what does AEO mean?" or "what is the definition of answer engine optimisation?" — query types that are both high-volume and highly valuable for establishing topical authority.
        </p>
      </section>

