            <strong>AEO and SEO are complementary disciplines with shared technical foundations but distinct optimisation targets, content requirements, and commercial outcomes.</strong>
            Neither replaces the other. For a fuller treatment of this relationship, see our <a href="/aeo-vs-seo/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">AEO vs SEO comparison guide</a>.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-8 space-y-4">
          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Shared Foundations</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Both AEO and SEO require strong technical foundations: fast page load times, mobile responsiveness, clean crawlability, logical site architecture, and HTTPS. Answer engines, like traditional search engines, will not select content from pages they cannot efficiently access and render. Technical SEO is a prerequisite for AEO, not an alternative to it.
            </p>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Both disciplines also require topical authority — a domain that demonstrates comprehensive, consistent expertise in a subject area through multiple related pages. A site with breadth and depth on a topic is more likely to be selected as an answer source than one with isolated pages, regardless of how well those pages are individually optimised.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Where They Diverge</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              The divergence begins at content structure. Traditional SEO tolerates — and sometimes rewards — comprehensive, long-form content where the core answer is buried within extensive supporting context. AEO demands the opposite: the core answer must appear immediately after the heading that targets the query, in 40–60 words, before any supporting context is provided.
            </p>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Schema usage represents another point of divergence. In traditional SEO, structured data is helpful for rich results but optional for strong organic rankings. In AEO, FAQPage schema is not optional — it is the primary mechanism for marking content as explicitly designed for answer extraction. Pages without FAQ schema compete at a structural disadvantage for featured snippet and AI Overview selection.
            </p>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Finally, success metrics diverge sharply. Traditional SEO measures success by ranking position, organic click-through rate, and traffic. AEO measures success by answer selection rate — the proportion of target queries for which your content is selected as the direct answer — and by brand visibility in zero-click answer positions. A page that holds a featured snippet for a high-volume query may generate relatively few clicks but significant brand exposure and authority.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 6: AEO vs GEO in Detail -->
      <section id="aeo-vs-geo-detail" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>AEO vs GEO: Understanding the Hierarchy</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>AEO is a focused subset of generative engine optimisation (GEO) — every AEO tactic is a GEO tactic, but GEO encompasses a broader strategic scope.</strong>
        </p>

        <p>
          AEO concentrates on the direct-answer layer: featured snippets, AI Overviews, People Also Ask, voice responses. The optimisation questions are: Is my content structured for extraction? Does it appear in answer boxes? Is the schema correctly implemented?
        </p>

        <p>
          GEO extends the question to the full AI search landscape: Is my brand recognised as a distinct entity in AI knowledge graphs? Is my content being cited by ChatGPT, Perplexity, and Copilot when users ask about my category? Does my <code class="bg-ink-800 text-[#BFE9E1] px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs border border-[var(--line)]">llms.txt</code> file provide AI crawlers with an accurate, curated entry point? Are my AI crawler access policies correctly configured? Are my entity records consistent across Wikidata, LinkedIn, Companies House, and my Organisation schema?
        </p>

        <p>
          For practitioners building their first AI search programme, AEO provides a focused starting point with measurable, trackable outcomes: featured snippet ownership, AI Overview appearances, PAA positions. Once AEO fundamentals are in place, the programme can expand into the broader GEO discipline — entity authority, LLM citation monitoring, and cross-platform presence strategy.
        </p>

        <p>
          GEOoptimised delivers both. Our <a href="/aeo-services/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">AEO services</a> are the entry point; our full <a href="/geo-services/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO services</a> programme covers the complete discipline.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 7: Core AEO Concepts -->
      <section id="core-concepts" class="anchor-top mb-16">
        <div class="prose-dark">
          <h2>Core AEO Concepts Every Practitioner Should Know</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>Beyond the primary definitions, effective AEO practice relies on a set of core concepts that inform content decisions, schema implementation, and performance measurement.</strong>
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-8 space-y-4">
          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Inverted Pyramid Structure</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              The inverted pyramid is the primary content pattern for AEO. The most important information — the direct answer — appears first. Supporting context, methodology, and elaboration follow. This mirrors how answer engines extract content: they take the first relevant, complete passage under a matching heading. Pages that bury the answer fail extraction regardless of overall quality.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Position Zero</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Position zero is the colloquial term for a featured snippet appearing above all organic results on a Google SERP. It is called "zero" because it precedes the traditional first organic result. Holding position zero for a high-volume query provides significant brand visibility — often at higher impression rates than the first organic position, though frequently with lower click-through rates due to zero-click answer satisfaction.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Zero-Click Search</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              A zero-click search is a query that is resolved without the user clicking through to any web page. The answer engine delivers the complete response directly on the results page or voice interface. A significant proportion of Google searches result in zero clicks. AEO optimises for this environment: brand presence in a zero-click answer generates authority and familiarity even without a site visit.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">E-E-A-T</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              E-E-A-T stands for Experience, Expertise, Authoritativeness, and Trustworthiness — the quality framework Google's quality raters use to evaluate content, and a proxy for what answer engines consider when selecting sources. For AEO, E-E-A-T is demonstrated through author credentials, original research, external citations, factual accuracy, and transparent sourcing. YMYL (Your Money, Your Life) content — medical, financial, legal — is evaluated against E-E-A-T standards most rigorously.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Topical Authority</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Topical authority is the degree to which a domain is recognised as a comprehensive, reliable source on a specific subject area. It is built by publishing a structured set of interlinked pages that together cover a topic from every relevant angle — creating what is sometimes called a "topical cluster" or "content hub." AEO selection rates improve significantly on domains with strong topical authority because answer engines gain confidence that the source is genuinely expert rather than producing isolated content.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Knowledge Graph</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              A knowledge graph is a structured database of entities and the relationships between them. Google's Knowledge Graph underpins both featured snippets and AI Overviews — it is the system that allows Google to understand that "GEOoptimised" refers to a specific UK-based agency in the generative engine optimisation category. Brands with a well-populated Knowledge Graph entry — evidenced by a Knowledge Panel in Google Search — are better positioned for AEO and GEO outcomes than brands without entity graph representation.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="prose-dark mt-8">
          <p>
            These concepts are put into practice through the techniques covered in the <a href="/aeo-best-practices/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">AEO best practices guide</a> and explained mechanically in the <a href="/how-aeo-works/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">How AEO Works guide</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- FAQ Accordion -->
